\begin_layout Abstract
Many creatures ranging from geckos to beetles can easily climb on surfaces
 with the help of hairy adhesive pads on their legs.
 The hairy pad's design allows the animal to rapidly switch between strong
 adhesion during attachment and weak adhesion during detachment.
 Several studies explain this mechanism based on the asymmetric geometry
 of the hairs, which imparts direction dependent adhesion properties.
 Here, we propose a mechanism for controlling adhesion of a hairy pad based
 on a simple spring model.
 We show that the adhesion force can be decreased just by slightly tilting
 the pad during pull-off.
 Larger number of hairs are shown to decrease adhesion by a larger factor
 for a similar tilt.
 Further, deformation of the pad's soft backing layer can trigger its spontaneou
s detachment at low tilt angles due to an elastic recoil effect.
 Our model provides a new approach to switch the adhesion state in bio-inspired
 synthetic array-based adhesives without the need of asymmetric structures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Over the past few decades, there has been numerous studies to understand
 how animals such as geckos and insects are able to walk on surfaces in
 any direction defying gravity.
 A microscopic observation reveals that, in many cases, animals have a dense
 array of hairy structures at the end of their legs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN198,RN59"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These hairy adhesive pads help the animal to stay attached to any surface,
 supporting its weight, and detach easily at will.
 Previous attempts to theoretically explain adhesion in hairy pads
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN40,RN120"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 has followed two fundamental approaches: either by energy balance, or by
 force balance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the energy balance approach, adhesion is characterized by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

work of adhesion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (W
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
adh
\end_layout

\end_inset

) which is the energy required to separate a pad from the surface.
 During detachment, elastic energy stored in the hair is dissipated, which
 increases W
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
adh
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and thus adhesion is enhanced
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN29,RN114"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Detachment of an individual hair can be explained based on Kendall's peeling
 theory
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN147"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which predicts low forces at high peeling angles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the force balance approach, adhesion is characterized by pull-off force,
 F
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
p
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (or stress, σ
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
p
\end_layout

\end_inset

), which is the maximum force necessary to separate two surfaces from contact.
 Based on a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cohesive zone model
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, Hui et.
 al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN72"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 had identified two regimes of hair detachment: 1) a flaw sensitive regime,
 where contact failure occurs due to crack propagation leading to low σ
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
p
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 2) a flaw insensitive regime, where the contact interface fails simultaneously
, leading to high σ
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
p
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Tian et.
 al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN230"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 had shown that the spatula shaped hair tips in a gecko's toe allows it
 change adhesion by three orders of magnitude by laterally sliding and controlli
ng the pulling angle.
 Federle
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN20"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 had further argued that the curved shape of hairs helps the pad to stay
 attached when pulled proximally, and easily detached by elastic recoil
 when pushed distally.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theories presented so far suggests that low detachment force of a hairy
 pad can be attained by 1) increasing the stress concentration by peeling
 the pad at high angles, or 2) laterally shearing the pad before pull-off,
 which requires the hairs to have an asymmetric geometry.
 Fabricating synthetic mimics with asymmetric micro hair structures however
 are generally difficult.
 It is thus desired to have alternate strategies to achieve reversible adhesion
 suited for practical applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work, we present a new method of detachment by changing the tilt
 of the pad relative to the surface.
 Tilting the pad will result in an unbalanced elastic force due to the deformati
on of hairs, which can potentially reduce the net pull-off force.
 To investigate this, we model the hairy pad by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spring contact model
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN117"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This model is based on the force-balance approach, which assumes the hairy
 pad to behave like an array of springs.
 We hope our work to provide new strategies to control adhesion force of
 an artificial micro-pillar adhesive, with applications in bio inspired
 robotic systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The hairy pad is assumed to be a one dimensional system of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 hairs, each behaving like a spring with spring constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{h}$
\end_inset

, and natural length, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,0}$
\end_inset

 (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Schematic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The hairs are attached to a backing layer, assumed to be another spring
 with spring constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{b}$
\end_inset

, and natural length, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{b,0}$
\end_inset

.
 The hairs are spaced apart by width 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 The pad is oriented at a tilt angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, while making contact with a flat smooth surface.
 The center of the pad is at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 from the surface.
 Each hair can attain a maximum length, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}$
\end_inset

, before pull-off, such that its pull-off force, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{p}=k_{h}\left(l_{h,p}-l_{h,0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The pad is pulled vertically upward while maintaining the given tilt angle
 with the surface.
 Excess torque in the system is assumed to be balanced externally and is
 not considered for our analysis.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{net}$
\end_inset

 is the net force on the pad at a particular instant during the detachment
 process and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{adh}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum force required to detach 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 hairs from the surface.
 We consider three modes of detachment, described below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Figure1-model_schematic.svg
	lyxscale 50

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Spring contact model of a hairy adhesive pad with a soft backing layer.
 The pad is oriented at a tilt angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, with the surface.
 The pad has a total number of hairs, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

, of which, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 number of hairs are in contact with the surface at a particular instant.
 The left most hair in contact is at its maximum length, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}$
\end_inset

, just before it detaches.
 The arrow along the surface indicates positive axis direction, and its
 corresponding origin is labeled as thus.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Schematic"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Sequential detachment:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>0\textdegree$
\end_inset

, the hairs will detach sequentially from left to right.
 Suppose at a particular instant (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Schematic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 hairs in contact with the surface.
 The origin is assumed to lie at the midpoint along the surface where the
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 hairs are making contact.
 The pad is at a vertical distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

, from the origin.
 For a particular tilt angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, the net force on the whole pad at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 from the surface is,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{net}\left(d,n,\theta\right)=\stackrel[i=1]{n}{\sum}k_{h}\left(l_{h,i}-l_{h,0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,i}$
\end_inset

 is the length of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 hair, which is at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from the origin.
 From simple geometry, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,i}=d'-x\tan\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting in above and noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\stackrel[i=1]{n}{\sum}x=0$
\end_inset

 by symmetry, we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{net}\left(d,n,\theta\right)=nk_{h}\left(d'-l_{h,0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From geometry, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

 is related as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{\tan\theta}-\frac{d'}{\tan\theta}=\frac{\left(N_{t}-1\right)w\cos\theta}{2}-\frac{\left(n-1\right)w\cos\theta}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eliminating 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

 from the above two equations, we find the net force on the pad as a function
 of distance to be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{net}\left(d,n,\theta\right)=nk_{h}\left(d-l_{h,0}-\frac{N_{t}-n}{2}w\sin\theta\right)\label{eq:force_n_d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a particular value of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is valid until a certain distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{max}$
\end_inset

, above which its left most hair will detach.
 Just before detachment, this hair will be at its maximum length, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}$
\end_inset

.
 Once again from geometry, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{max}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}$
\end_inset

 is related as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{l_{h,p}}{\tan\theta}-\frac{d_{max}}{\tan\theta}=\left(n-1\right)w\cos\theta-\frac{\left(N_{t}-1\right)w\cos\theta}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}=\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}}+l_{h,0}$
\end_inset

 in above and simplifying, we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{max}\left(n,\theta\right)=l_{h,0}+\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}}+\left(\frac{N_{t}+1}{2}-n\right)w\sin\theta\label{eq:d_max}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is valid for 
\begin_inset Formula $d\leq d_{max}$
\end_inset

.
 We can substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{max}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to get the force at which the left most hair detaches from the surface:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{net}\left(n,\theta\right)=nf_{p}-\frac{n\left(n-1\right)}{2}k_{h}w\sin\theta & \qquad & d=d_{max}\label{eq:seq_detach}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seq_detach"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is the maximum force necessary to detach one hair of the pad when there
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 hairs in contact.
 During this sequential detachment of hairs, there exists a maximum in force
 at a particular number of contacts, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{max}$
\end_inset

.
 Differentiating equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seq_detach"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and equating it to zero we find:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{max}=\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w\sin\theta}+\frac{1}{2}\label{eq:n_max}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the above in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seq_detach"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the maximum adhesion force of a pad during a sequential detachment of
 its 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 hairs will be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{adh}\left(\theta\right) & = & \left\{ \begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{f_{p}}{2}\left[\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w\sin\theta}+1\right]+\frac{k_{h}w\sin\theta}{8} & \qquad & N_{t}\geq N_{max}\\
N_{t}f_{p}-\frac{N_{t}\left(N_{t}-1\right)}{2}k_{h}w\sin\theta & \qquad & N_{t}<N_{max}
\end{array}\right.\label{eq:seq_adh}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Simultaneous detachment:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All hairs detach simultaneously when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0\textdegree$
\end_inset

.
 Here, the hairy pad shows the maximum possible adhesion, as given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{adh}=F_{max}=N_{t}f_{p}\label{eq:simul_detach}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Force as a function of distance can be obtained by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $n=N_{t}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Spontaneous detachment by propagation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider a special case of sequential detachment where even the pad
 backing layer deforms, along with the hairs.
 When a hair detaches from the surface, the backing layer undergoes an elastic
 recoil due to the stored elastic energy.
 Suppose the backing layer spring relaxes upward by a length 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

 (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Schematic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 hairs in contact, the force balance before and after a hair detaches is
 given respectively by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\stackrel[i=1]{n}{\sum}k_{h}\left(l_{h,i}-l_{h,0}\right)=k_{b}\left(l_{b}-l_{b,0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\stackrel[i=1]{n-1}{\sum}k_{h}\left(l_{h,i}+\Delta l-l_{h,0}\right)=k_{b}\left(l_{b}-\Delta l-l_{b,0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving the above two equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

, we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta l=\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}\left(n-1\right)+k_{b}}\label{eq:backing_deform}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The length difference between the detached hair just before it breaks contact
 and its adjacent hair is 
\begin_inset Formula $w\sin\theta$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l>w\sin\theta$
\end_inset

, the adjacent hair will be stretched more than its maximum length (
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}$
\end_inset

), and thus will also detach.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backing_deform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

 increases with every loss of hair contact due to decreasing value of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that, hair detachment will propagate and the pad completely
 breaks contact with the surface.
 The critical number of hairs in contact, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{c}$
\end_inset

, below which detachment propagates for a given tilt angle can be calculated
 by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backing_deform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into the above inequality condition, to get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{c}=\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w\sin\theta}-\frac{k_{b}}{k_{h}}+1\label{eq:prop_nc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the above in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:d_max"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we can find the critical distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{c}$
\end_inset

, above which detachment propagates:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{c}=\left(\frac{k_{b}}{k_{h}}+\frac{N_{t}-1}{2}\right)\sin\theta\label{eq:d_c}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prop_nc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can also be rearranged to give us the critical tilt angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{c}$
\end_inset

, below which detachment propagates for a given pad with 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 hairs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{c}=\arcsin\left[\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w}\left(\frac{1}{\frac{k_{b}}{k_{h}}+N_{t}-1}\right)\right]\label{eq:prop_thetac}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hairs will propagate when 
\begin_inset Formula $n<N_{c}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $d>d_{c}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta<\theta_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we assume the hairs to be softer than the backing layer (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{b}/k_{h}>1$
\end_inset

), then from equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:n_max"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prop_nc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{c}<N_{max}$
\end_inset

.
 Spontaneous detachment of the pad occurs only after it has reached maximum
 adhesion force by sequential detachment of hairs.
 So in this case, for a given pad with 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 hairs, the adhesion force will be given by the same equation as for sequential
 detachment (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seq_adh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The adhesion remains unaffected by the backing layer deformation.
 It only affects the dynamics of detachment.
 The hairs lose contact spontaneously when 
\begin_inset Formula $n<N_{c}$
\end_inset

, independent of the speed at which the pad is retracted.
 One the other hand, the net force as a function of distance will be given
 by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d"
