\begin_layout Paragraph
Detachment mechanism:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The three modes of detachment can be understood by looking at the net force
 as hairs detaches from the surface.
 Let us look at the case when the pad has 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}=25$
\end_inset

 hairs and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}=1$
\end_inset

.
 From equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:d_max"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:simul_detach"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:d_c"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we get the force-distance curves for each mode of detachment (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Mechanism-of-detachment"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 We consider two cases: a pad with a stiff backing (
\begin_inset Formula $k_{b}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

) and a pad with a soft backing (
\begin_inset Formula $k_{b}/k_{h}=10$
\end_inset

 ).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At small distances, all hairs of the pad are in contact and under compression,
 showing a linear Hookian response as the pad is pulled upwards maintaining
 a tilt.
 On further pulling, the hairs of the pad with a higher tilt will start
 to detach first, followed by the ones with a lower tilt.
 The force curves for the pad with a stiff backing shows a characteristic
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

saw-tooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 shaped fluctuation, indicating the sequential events of individual hair
 detachment as the pad is retracted away from the surface.
 In the case for the pad with a soft backing, such fluctuations are minimized
 due to the backing layer's deformation after each hair detaches, leading
 to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dampened
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 force response.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increasing the tilt of the pad decreases its maximum force or adhesion.
 Tilting the pad compresses the hairs at one end and stretches them on the
 other end.
 The balance of the attractive and repulsive elastic forces of the hairs
 ultimately results in a decrease in the net force.
 In comparison, when there is no tilt, all the hairs detach simultaneously
 after a distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}=1$
\end_inset

, and the pad shows the maximum possible adhesion.
 Overall, we see that the adhesion force at a particular tilt is same for
 both types of backing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a soft backing, we observe that at a tilt angle of 3°, the force abruptly
 drops to zero at a certain distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}_{c}\simeq1.15$
\end_inset

 (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:d_c"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 This represents the spontaneous propagation of hair detachment due to elastic
 recoil of the backing layer once the 15
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 hair (
\begin_inset Formula $N_{c}=10$
\end_inset

) snaps off.
 No such force drop is seen when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=6\textdegree$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{c}$
\end_inset

 is less than 1 (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prop_nc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 All its hairs have already detached sequentially before it could trigger
 a spontaneous detachment.
 So in this case, the force-distance curves look very similar to that of
 the pad with a stiff backing.
 
\end_layout

