\begin_layout Paragraph
Effect of tilt on adhesion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reduction of adhesion during detachment (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:reversib"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is compared for different tilt angles, number of hairs and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}$
\end_inset

 (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Adhesion-force-of"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 For a fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}$
\end_inset

, adhesion force shows a maximum with increasing tilt angle.
 This is because, the net force on a tilted pad depends on a balance between
 the stretched hairs, on one end, and the compressed hairs, on the other
 end.
 When the pad is tilted, initially the compressed hair dominates in its
 contribution to the new force and thus adhesion force initially decreases,
 increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 On further tilting, the number of stretched hairs increases and eventually
 dominates the force contribution.
 This results in an increase in adhesion force at large tilt angles, and
 thus decreases 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can calculate the maximum reduction factor from the minima of adhesion
 w.r.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seq_adh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) to get 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{min}=f_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding tilt angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{max}$
\end_inset

, for maximum reduction factor, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{max}$
\end_inset

, will be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{alignedat}{1}\theta_{max} & =\arcsin\left(\frac{2f_{p}}{k_{h}w}\right)\\
r_{max} & =\frac{F_{max}}{F_{min}}=N_{t}
\end{alignedat}
\label{eq:rev_max}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

