\begin_layout Paragraph
Limitation of tilt:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There exists a limit to how much one can tilt a hairy pad, depending on
 the pad's geometry and material properties.
 Suppose the hair has a maximum linear elastic strain limit, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{m}$
\end_inset

, and natural length, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,0}$
\end_inset

.
 Based on Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Schematic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, if the right most hair is compressed to its elastic limit, we can show
 from simple geometry, that, the corresponding maximum limit in tilt angle
 is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{limit}=\arctan\frac{l_{h,0}\varepsilon_{m}}{\left(N_{t}-1\right)w}\label{eq:theta_limit}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{limit}$
\end_inset

 represents the elastic limit in tilting a hairy pad.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{max}$
\end_inset

 must be less than 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{limit}$
\end_inset

 to allow maximum possible reduction in adhesion.
 Else, the pad's reduction factor will be limited to its value at 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{limit}$
\end_inset

, as per Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Adhesion-force-of"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We see a trade-off in the conditions for reducing adhesion or to trigger
 spontaneous detachment.
 Low 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}$
\end_inset

 and high 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 are suitable for reater reduction in adhesion, while high 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}$
\end_inset

 and low 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 are favorable to trigger spontaneous detachment.
 At the same time, the hairy pad must have an optimal value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{max}$
\end_inset

 does not exceed 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{limit}$
\end_inset

.
 Depending on whether a higher range of controllable adhesion or an instantaneou
s detachment is more desirable, one can utilize Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Adhesion-force-of"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Critical-tilt-angle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, together with equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theta_limit"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, as design maps in the fabrication of micro-pillar adhesives suited for
 the required application.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In live animals, as far as our knowledge, there is no experimental evidence
 that the animal can modulate adhesion by changing its pad's tilt.
 Let us consider the case of a dock beetle.
 It was previously reported that
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN79"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, its pointed tipped hair shows a pull off force and spring constant of
 0.1 μN and 0.2 Nm
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
-1
\end_layout

\end_inset

 respectively, while its disc tipped hair has the corresponding values of
 0.9 μN and 0.7 Nm
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
-1
\end_layout

\end_inset

 receptively.
 The beetle's hairs are approximately 50 μm long, spaced 10 μm apart.
 Let us assume the hairs to have a elastic strain limit of 25%, which is
 a reasonable estimate considering that the curved geometry of its hairs
 makes it more flexible.
 We can thus calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}$
\end_inset

 for the beetle's pointed and disc tipped hairs to be 0.05 and 0.13 respectively.
 Since both types of hairs are present in the beetle's pad, let us thus
 assume an effective value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}$
\end_inset

 = 0.1.
 Assuming that 100 hairs of the pad are in contact during locomotion, a
 one dimensional analogue of the system will put 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}=10$
\end_inset

 in our model.
 From equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rev_max"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theta_limit"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{max}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{limit}$
\end_inset

 are calculated to be 11.5° and 7.9°, respectively.
 Thus, for the beetle, the elastic limit imposed by the pad allows it to
 only tilt it by 7.9°, about 3.6° lower than the tilt necessary to achieve
 maximum reduction factor.
 However, we see from Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Adhesion-force-of"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that, at a 7.9° tilt, the redution factor is 9.6, close to the theoretical
 maximum (10).
 The beetle can reduce its adhesion force by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10$
\end_inset

 by tilting its pad by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim8\textdegree$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the model seems consistent with nature's design of the beetle's pad.
 A detailed experimental investigation however is essential to prove if
 such a tilting mechanism is indeed employed by animals to switch adhesion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have proposed a method to control the adhesion of a hairy adhesive pad
 by changing the tilt.
 Increasing the tilt reduces adhesion due to the elastic force balance between
 the compressed and stretched hairs.
 Based on a simple spring model, we show that increasing the number of hairy
 structures enhances the range of adjustable adhesion force, which highlights
 the advantage of a hairy design for controlling adhesion.
 Further, having a soft backing layer can trigger a spontaneous detachment
 of hairs as a result of its elastic recoil.
 High 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 and low 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}$
\end_inset

 are suitable for reducing adhesion by a larger factor, while, low 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

, high 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}$
\end_inset

 and softer backing layer favor spontaneous detachment.
 The model is consistent with the natural design of a dock beetle's hairy
 pad and provides new strategies to reversibly control adhesion in bio-inspired
 artificial adhesives.
